Dataset Summary:¶

  • Trip data: in the dataset, there are total 354152 trips, range from 2014-09-01 to 2015-08-31. That is, one year of trip data. There are two types of customer: Subscriber (annual or 30-day member) and Customer (24-hour or 30-day member).
  • Weather data: There are 1825 weather information for same date range of trip data, that is 365 days of weather record for each City. Briefly, weather information have records of temperature, humidity, sea level pressure, visibility, wind speed, precipitation, cloud cover, wind direction, and special events. Special events are 4 different evens labeled as Rain, Fog, Fog-Rain and Rain-Thunderstorm. But there are lots of data without special event label, which might be a normal day instead.
  • Station data: There are total 76 stations. As described in the assignment information, 5 of them are moved to a new stations, that is 23, 25, 49, 69, 72 to 85, 86, 87, 88, 89, respectively. And station 89 further moved to station 90. So there are total 70 live stations.

Potential Issues:¶

  • Missing values: there is no missing value in trip and station data, but weather data have some missing values.

1.3 Data Preprocessing¶

I'll do following steps to preprocess data first:

  • Add zipcode to station_df
  • Update station number (move old stations to new stations)
  • Standardize 'Date' in both trip_df and weather_df
  • Impute missing value in weather_df

# Add zipcode to station_df
def get_zip(city_name):
    if city_name == 'San Francisco':
        return 94107
    elif city_name == 'Redwood City':
        return 94063
    elif city_name == 'Mountain View':
        return 94041
    elif city_name == 'San Jose':
        return 95113
    elif city_name == 'Palo Alto':
        return 94301
    
station_df['Zip'] = station_df['City'].apply(lambda x: get_zip(x))

Impute missing value in weather data¶

The weather data contained a lot of missing values. I'll use the following strategies to impute these missing values.

  • 'Events' with NaN values will be considered as a 'Normal' day.
  • Other missing weather values will be imputed with the last known value in previous days. (forward-filling)

Note: impute missing value should actually be done after data exploration. I did it here because 1) I'll use 'Normal' label for weather in the following analysis, 2) other missing weather values are very few and I won't explore it later.

In [28]:
# Fill missing value
weather_df.loc[weather_df.Events.isnull(), 'Events'] = "Normal"
weather_df.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)

Explore Station 70¶

Since station 70 has more data, I want to take a deep exploration of this station to see any factors will affect the net rate (trip ends - trip started) of this station.

In [42]:
def create_station_df(station_id):
    """
    Create a DataFrame for the station trip data given a station number.
    The station-trip data contains hourly trip info, station info and weather info for this particular station.
    
    type station_id: int
    rtype: pandas DataFrame
    """
    trip_station_df = trip_df[trip_df['Start Station'] == station_id]
    grouped_start = trip_station_df.groupby(["Date_Start", "Hour_Start"])["Trip ID"].count().reset_index(name="Out_Count")
    grouped_end = trip_station_df.groupby(["Date_End", "Hour_End"])["Trip ID"].count().reset_index(name="In_Count")

    # create new df
    start_date = dt.datetime(2014, 9, 1)
    end_date = dt.datetime(2015, 8, 31)
    index = pd.date_range(start_date, end_date, freq='H') # Hourly index
    df = pd.DataFrame(index=index)
    df['Station'] = station_id
    df['Date'] = df.index.date
    df['Day_Of_Month'] = df.index.day
    df['Hour'] = df.index.hour
    df['Month'] = df.index.month
    df['Weekday'] = df.index.weekday + 1
    
    # get out_count and in_count number, then calculate net rate
    df = pd.merge(df, grouped_start, left_on=['Date','Hour'], right_on=['Date_Start','Hour_Start'], how='left')
    df = pd.merge(df, grouped_end, left_on=['Date','Hour'], right_on=['Date_End','Hour_End'], how='left')

    df = df.drop(columns=['Date_Start', 'Hour_Start', 'Date_End', 'Hour_End'])
    df = df.fillna(0)
    df[['Out_Count','In_Count']] = df[['Out_Count','In_Count']].astype(int)
    df['Net_Rate'] = df['In_Count'] - df['Out_Count']
    
    # Get zipcode for the station
    zipcode = station_df[station_df['Id'] == station_id].iloc[0]['Zip']
    
    # Merge weather data
    df = pd.merge(df, weather_df[weather_df['Zip'] == zipcode], left_on=['Date'], right_on=['Date'], how='left')
    
    # Fill Normal Events
    #df.loc[df.Events.isnull(), 'Events'] = "Normal"
    
    # Return df for the station
    return df

2. Modeling: Approach and Evaluation¶

Now we explored the data and find several important factors for the net rate of a station in a given hour. We move to the modeling part.

2.1 Prepare Data¶

First, I'll combine all individual station data into a whole dataframe.

Feature Engineering: more features¶

From the analysis above, we have seen that hourly net rate bike usage is considerably different on weekdays as compared to weekends. So I'll add a binary feature ('Is_Weekend') for whether any given day is a weekend. Similarly, I also add another binary feature ('Is_Holiday') for whether any given day is a holiday in US.

In [169]:
# Add Is_Weekend feature
df['Is_Weekend'] = df['Weekday'].isin([6,7])

# Add Is_Holiday feature
from pandas.tseries.holiday import USFederalHolidayCalendar as calendar
cal = calendar()
holidays = cal.holidays(start=dt.datetime(2014, 9, 1), end=dt.datetime(2015, 8, 31))
df['Is_Holiday'] = df['Date'].isin(holidays)

The Dock Count for each station describes the intensity of usage of the station, this is unique for each station and probably contribute to the pattern of net rate. so I'll extract dock count data from the station_df and merge it into the final data frame.

In [170]:
# Add Dock Count to the station
df = pd.merge(df, station_df[['Id','Dock Count']], left_on=['Station'], right_on=['Id'], how='left')
df = df.drop(columns=['Id'])

Train-Test Split¶

In order to ensure that the model is evaluated properly, I split data into 2 separate sets: training set and test set. Since this is time series data, I don't want my model to train on future data points which would not be available at the time of prediction.

I'm not sure if month has impact on hourly net rate (from data exploration, influence is not obvious), but I assume each day in a month should perform similar. So I use first 24 days in months as training set, and the rest days of months as testing set. This is around 80%-20% split of training and testing set.

  • train: day 1-24
  • test: day 24 - end of month
In [296]:
train = df_dummies[df_dummies['Day_Of_Month'] <= 24]
test = df_dummies[df_dummies['Day_Of_Month'] > 24]

features = [x for x in train.columns if x not in ['Day_Of_Month', 'Out_Count', 'In_Count', 'Net_Rate']]

X_train = train[features]
X_test = test[features]
y_train = train['Net_Rate']
y_test = test['Net_Rate']

2.2 Baseline Model¶

The baseline model here is a statistic model. Here I simply use the mean value of hourly net rate for each station in the training set as the predicted hourly net rate. This is the simplest model which do not use any time (except for hour of the day) and weather features.

In [282]:
def get_mean_net_rate(station_id, hour_of_day):

    return mean_net_rate

    return y_predict

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from math import sqrt

def calc_rmse(y_actual, y_predict):
    return sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_actual, y_predict))

def plot_feature_importance(model, features, X_train):
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

    # Print the feature ranking
    print("Feature ranking:")

    for f in range(X_train.shape[1]):
        print("%d. feature %s (%f)" % (f + 1, features[indices[f]], importances[indices[f]]))

    # Plot the feature importances of the forest
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.title("Feature importances",size=16)
    plt.barh(range(X_train.shape[1]), importances[indices],
           color="steelblue", align="center")
    plt.yticks(range(X_train.shape[1]), [features[index] for index in indices], size=14), #{'rotate':45})
    plt.ylim([X_train.shape[1],-1])
    plt.xticks(size=12)
    plt.show()

Hyperparamter tuning using grid search and cross-validation¶

Note: Normally, we need to set aside a validation set to validate time series data and should not use cross-validation. This is because it ignore the temporal components inherent in the problem. But for this particular problem, I assume the net rate is independent of the day of the month. So I'll use cross-validation to find the hyperparameter here.

Note: For random forest, usually there is no need to reduce feature dimensionality if feature space is not too high (in our case, 33 features). Here for saving running time, I will only use first 12 features to perform grid search. RMSE will be used as the scoring criteria.

3. Conclusions and Further Steps¶

Here is a brief overview of conclusion and possible future steps. Please see pdf reports for more detail.

3.1 Conclusions¶

Important Features

- Station
- Hour
- Dock Count
- Time Related Features: Weekday, Is_Weekend, Month
- Weather Related Features: WindDirDegrees, Gust Speed, Humidity, Dew Point, Temperature, Wind Speed

Results

- Baseline model: test set RMSE: 0.5566
- Random Forest Model: test set RMSE: 0.5485

Random Forest Model perform slighly better than the baseline model.

3.2 Future Steps¶

Feature Engineering:

- Consider geo data, nearby station's traffic/net rate may also have influences
- Incorporate population and/or demographic data of users.

Model Building:

- Further optimize the Random Forest Model or try other tree based models such as Gradient Boosting Regression
- Use PCA to reduce dimentionality and then try other ML algorithms
- Build model for each group/cluster, such as build model for different zipcode 
- Time series model, such as ARIMA
